First we compute the area A of the shape. This is given by

\begin{align*}A &=\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}1+\sin(x) dx \\  &= x\big|_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}-\cos\big|_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}\\ &=\pi-\cos(\pi/2)+\cos(-\pi/2)\\&=\pi\end{align*}

The coordinates of the centroid are computed using the formulas

\[\bar{x}=\frac{1}{\pi}\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}x(1+\sin(x))dx\]

and

\[\bar{y}=\frac{1}{\pi}\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}\frac{1}{2}(1+\sin(x))^2dx\]

We will compute $\bar{x}$ first.

\begin{align*}\bar{x}&=\frac{1}{\pi}\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}x+x\sin(x)dx\\ &=\frac{1}{\pi}\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}x dx+\frac{1}{\pi}\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}x\sin(x)dx\\
&= 0+\frac{1}{\pi}\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}x\sin(x)dx
\end{align*}

The first integral is zero because the function is odd. For the second
we can use integration by parts.

\begin{align*}\int x\sin(x)dx &= -x\cos(x)+\int \cos(x)dx\\&=-x\cos(x)+\sin(x)+C \end{align*}

That means if we plug in the limits for the definite integral we get

\begin{align*}\bar{x}&=1/\pi(-x\cos(x)+\sin(x))\big|_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}\\&=1/\pi(\sin(\pi/2)-\sin(-\pi/2))\\&=2/\pi \end{align*}

Now we compute $\bar{y}$

\begin{align*}\bar{y}&=\frac{1}{\pi}\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}\frac{1}{2}(1+\sin(x))^2dx\\&= \frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}1+2\sin(x)+\sin(x)^2dx\\&=\frac{1}{2\pi}\Big(\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}1dx+2\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}\sin(x)dx+\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}\sin(x)^2dx\Big)\\&=\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}\sin(x)^2dx\end{align*}

To compute this we note $\sin(x)^2=\frac{1-\cos(2x)}{2}$

\begin{align*}\int \sin(x)^2dx&=\int \frac{1-\cos(2x)}{2}dx\\&=\frac{x}{2}-\frac{1}{4}\sin(2x)+C\end{align*}

Hence

\begin{align*}\bar{y}&=\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{2\pi}(\frac{x}{2}-\frac{1}{4}\sin(2x))_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}\\&=\frac{3}{4}\end{align*}

Thus the centroid is $(\frac{2}{\pi},\frac{3}{4})$
